<section xml:id="sec_quotientRings" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Quotient Rings</title>
    
  <objectives xml:id="obj_quotientRings">
    <title>Guiding Questions</title>
    <introduction>
		<p>
      In this section, we'll seek to answer the questions:
    </p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      			
      <li>How can we use ideals to build new rings out of old?</li>
      <li>What sorts of ideals allow us to build domains? Fields?</li>
      <li>What is the First Isomorphism Theorem?</li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>
  <introduction>
    <p>
    		If the only rings that existed were polynomial rings, familiar systems of numbers like <m>\Z/m, \Z, \Q, \R, \C</m>, polynomial rings, and matrix rings, 
        there would still be enough to justify defining the concept of a ring and exploring its properties. 
    		However, these are not the only rings that exist. In this section, we explore a way of building new rings from old by means of ideals.
    		To better understand these new rings, we will also define two new classes of ideals: prime ideals, and maximal ideals.
    		We end by briefly connecting these rings to a familiar problem from high school algebra.
    </p>
</introduction>

<subsection xml:id="ssec_congruenceModuloI">
	<title>Congruence modulo <m>I</m></title>
	<p>
		The major concept of this section is the notion of congruence modulo <m>I</m>.
		One can reasonably think of this idea as a generalization of congruence modulo <m>m</m> in <m>\Z</m>.
	</p>


    <definition>
    <idx>congruence mod <m>I</m></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be a ring, <m>I</m> an ideal of <m>R</m>, and <m>a,b\in R</m>.
          We say <m>a</m> is
          <term>congruent to <m>b</m> modulo <m>I</m></term> if <m>b-a\in I</m>.
          If this is the case, we write <m>a + I = b + I</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <activity>
    		<statement>
    			<p>
    				Determine (with brief justification) whether <m>a + I = b + I</m> in the following rings <m>R</m>.
    			</p>
			<ol>
				<li><m>a = 9</m>, <m>b = 3</m>, <m>I = (6)</m>, <m>R = \Z</m></li>
				<li><m>a = 10</m>, <m>b = 4</m>, <m>I = (7)</m>, <m>R = \Z</m></li>
				<li><m>a = 9</m>, <m>b = 3</m>, <m>I = (6)</m>, <m>R = \Z[x]</m></li>
				<li><m>a = x^2+x-2</m>, <m>b = x-1</m>, <m>I = (x+1)</m>, <m>R = \Q[x]</m></li>
				<li> (<em>Challenge.</em>) <m>a = x^3</m>, <m>b = x^2+2x</m>, <m>I = (y-x^2, y-x-2)</m>, <m>R = \Q[x,y]</m></li>
			</ol>
		</statement>
		<solution>
			
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            We have <m>3-9 = -6 = (-1)\cdot 6\in (6)</m> so <m>9+(6) = 3+ (6)</m> in <m>\Z</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            We have <m>4-10 = -6\notin (7)</m> as <m>-6\neq 7k</m> for any <m>k\in\Z</m>. Thus 
            <m>10+(7)\neq 4+(7)</m> in <m>\Z</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>3-9 = -6 = (-1)\cdot 6\in (6)</m>. Thus <m>9+(6) = 3+(6)</m> in <m>\Z[x]</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>x-1-(x^2+x-2) = -x^2+1 = -(x-1)(x+1)\in (x+1)</m>. Thus <m>x-1+(x+1) = x^2+x-2 + (x+1)</m> 
            in <m>\Q[x]</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>x^3 - x^2 - 2x = x(x-2)(x+1) = -x(y-x^2) + x(y-x-2)</m>. Thus
            <me>x^3+(y-x^2,y-x-2) = x^2+x+ (y-x^2,y-x-2)</me>
            in <m>\Q[x,y]</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
		</solution>
	</activity>
    
    <exploration>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Given a ring <m>R</m>, ideal <m>I</m>,
          and <m>a\in R</m>, when is it the case that <m>a + I = 0 + I = I</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          When <m>a\in I</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exploration>

    <p>
      Observe that if <m>b-a \in I</m>,
      then there is some <m>x\in I</m> such that <m>b-a = x</m>,
      and so <m>b = a+x</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      The notation <m>a+I = b+I</m> is more than just notation. It is an equality of sets. 
      Given any ideal <m>I\subseteq R</m> and any <m>a\in R</m>, define 
      <me>a+I = \{a+i\mid i\in I\}</me>
      to be the set of all translates of <m>I</m> under <m>a</m>.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm_congruenceIsEquality">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>I\subseteq R</m> be an ideal and <m>a,b\in R</m>. Then <m>a</m> is congruent to <m>b</m> modulo <m>I</m> if and 
          only if we have equality of sets <m>a+I = b+I</m>.  
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>a</m> is congruent to <m>b</m> modulo <m>I</m>. Then <m>b-a\in I</m> so that <m> b = a+x</m> for some <m>x\in I</m>.
          Take any <m>i\in I</m>, then <m>b+i = a+(x+i)\in a+I</m> as <m>x+i\in I</m>. Thus <m>b+I\subseteq a+I</m>. Using instead <m>a = b+(-x)</m> 
          we have, similarly, that <m>a+I\subseteq b+I</m>. Thus <m>a+I = b+I</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>a+I = b+I</m>. Since <m>0\in I</m>, we know that <m>b = b+0\in b+I</m>. Since <m>a+I = b+I</m>, we have that <m>b\in a+I</m>. 
          Thus <m>b = a + x</m> for some <m>x\in I</m>. Equivalently <m>b-a=x\in I</m>. Thus <m>a</m> is congruent to <m>b</m> modulo <m>I</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>
    
    <definition xml:id="def_cosetsIdeal">
       <notation>
        <usage>a+I</usage>
        <description>Coset (ideal)</description>
      </notation>
      <idx><h>coset (ideal)</h></idx>

      <statement>
        <p>
          Given an ideal <m>I\subseteq R</m> in a commutative ring <m>R</m>. A <term>coset</term> of <m>I</m> is a set of the form 
          <me>a+I = \{a+i\mid i\in I\}.</me>
          The collection of all cosets is denoted <m>R/I</m> or <m>\bar{R}</m> if <m>I</m> is understood:
          <me>R/I = \{a+I\mid a\in R\}.</me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          We take a minute to observe that in <m>\Z</m> the notion of congruence: <m>a\equiv b</m> modulo <m>m</m> is equivalent to the definition here. 
          Indeed, any <m>m\in\Z</m> defines a principal ideal <m>(m)</m>. If <m>a\equiv_m b</m>, then <m>b-a = mk</m> for some <m>k\in \Z</m>. Hence, <m>b-a\in (m)</m>.
          And conversely, if <m>a+(m) = b+(m)</m>, then <m>b-a\in (m)</m>. Thus there exists <m>k\in\Z</m> with <m>b-a = mk</m> and so <m>a\equiv_mb</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          In particular, this is a successful generalization of the notion of congruence modulo <m>m</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    
    <p>
    	As was the case in <m>\Z_m</m>, congruence modulo <m>I</m> is an equivalence relation.
    </p>

    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be a ring and <m>I</m> an ideal of <m>R</m>.
          Then congruence modulo <m>I</m> is an equivalence relation on <m>R</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
      <p>
        Since <m>0\in I</m>, <m>a-a \in I</m> for all <m>a</m>,
        so <m>a + I = a+I</m> and the relation is reflexive.
      </p>
      <p>
        Moreover, if <m>b-a \in I</m>,
        then <m>-1(b-a) = a-b \in I</m>,
        so the relation is symmetric.
      </p>
      <p>
        If <m>b-a \in I</m> and <m>c-b\in I</m>,
        then <m>(b-a) + (c-b) = c-a \in I</m>,
        so the relation is transitive.
      </p>
    </proof>
    </theorem>
  
  </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="ssec_quotientRings">
      <title>Quotient Rings</title>
      
      <aside>
        <title>Notation for Integers Modulo <m>m</m></title>
        
        <p>
          It's standard practice to identify the principal ideal <m>(r)</m> with <m>r</m> when no confusion can arise.  
          In <m>\Z</m>, the set of equivalence classes modulo <m>(m)</m> is denoted by <m>\Z/m</m> instead of <m>\Z/(m)</m>. 
        </p>
      </aside>

    <p>
      The set of equivalence classes under this relation is denoted <m>R/I</m>. In particular, What is more, this is not merely a set of equivalence classes.
      As the next two theorems demonstrate, this set possesses two algebraic operations that extend naturally from those of <m>R</m>.
    </p>
    
    <theorem xml:id="thm_additionModI">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be a ring and <m>I</m> an ideal of <m>R</m>. If <m>a_1,a_2,b_1,b_2\in R</m> such that
          <m>a_1+I = a_2+I</m> and <m>b_1+I = b_2+I</m>, then <m>(a_1+b_1) + I = (a_2+b_2) + I</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>a_1+I = a_2+I</m> and <m>b_1+I = b_2+I</m>.
        Then <m>a_2-a_1 = x \in I</m> and <m>b_2-b_1 = y \in I</m>.
        Adding, we have 
        <me>(a_2+b_2) - (a_1+b_1) =(a_2-a_1) + (b_2-b_1) =  x+y \in I.</me>
        Thus, <m>(a_1+b_1) + I = (a_2+b_2) + I</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      Note that the only requirement in the proof of this theorem is that <m>I</m> is closed under addition.
    </p>
    
    <theorem xml:id="thm_multiplicationModI">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be a commutative ring and <m>I</m> an ideal of <m>R</m>.
          If <m>a_1,a_2,b_1,b_2\in R</m> such that
          <m>a_1+I = a_2+I</m> and <m>b_1+I = b_2+I</m>,
          then <m>a_1b_1 + I = a_2b_2 + I</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
      <p>
        As before, we observe that
        <m>a_2-a_1 = x\in I</m> and <m>b_2-b_1 = y\in I</m>.
        Write <m>a_2 = a_1+x</m> and <m>b_2 = b_1+y</m>.
        Then 
        <md>
          <mrow>  a_2b_2 =\amp (a_1+x)(b_1+y) </mrow> 
          <mrow> \amp= a_1b_1+a_1y +xb_1+xy</mrow>
          <mrow> \amp= a_1b_1 + \underbrace{(a_1y+xb_1+xy)}_{\in I}</mrow>
        </md>,
        so <m>a_2b_2-a_1b_1 = a_1y+xb_1+xy \in I</m>. Therefore <m>a_1b_1 + I = a_1b_1 + I</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      The preceeding proof used two properties of <m>I</m>: closure under addition and closure under multiplication by <m>R</m>.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      The previous two theorems together show that addition and multiplication on the set <m>R/I</m> is well-defined.
      As these operations are built on the operations of <m>R</m>, it will likely not surprise you to learn that the usual 
      <xref ref="def_ring" text="custom">axioms defining a ring</xref> also hold.
    </p>
    <theorem>
    <idx>quotient ring</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be a commutative ring, <m>I</m> an ideal of <m>R</m>, and <m>a,b\in R</m>.
          The set of cosets of <m>I</m>, denoted <m>\bar{R} = R/I</m>,
          is a commutative ring (called the <term>quotient ring</term> of <m>R</m> by <m>I</m>) with additive identity <m>0_R+I</m> and 
          multiplicative identity <m>1_R + I</m> under the following operations:
        </p>
        <md>
          <mrow>(a+I) + (b+I) &amp; := (a+b) + I</mrow>
          <mrow>(a+I) \cdot (b+I) &amp; := (ab) + I.</mrow>
        </md>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
      	  These operations were shown to be well-defined in <xref ref="thm_additionModI" /> and <xref ref="thm_multiplicationModI" />. We need to show 
          that, with these operations, all eight ring axioms hold and that multiplication is commutative. Take <m>a+I,b+I,c+I\in R/I</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          We begin with the additive axioms. For associativity:
          <md>
            <mrow>(a+I) + ((b+I)+(c+I)) \amp= (a+I) + ((b+c)+I) </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp= (a+(b+c))+I</mrow>
            <mrow>((a+I) + (b+I))+(c+I) \amp= ((a+b)+I) + (c+I) </mrow> 
            <mrow> \amp= ((a+b)+c)+I.</mrow>
          </md>
          Since <m>R</m> has associative addition we have <m>a+(b+c) = (a+b)+c</m> and so 
          <me>
            a+(b+c) +I = (a+b)+c + I
          </me>
          the cosets are equal.
        </p>
        <p>
          For commutativity:
          <me>(a+I) + (b+I) = (a+b) + I = (b+a)+I = (b+I)+(a+I).</me>
        </p>
        <p>
          For identity:
          <me>(0_R+I)+(a+I) = (0_R+a) + I = a+I</me>
          as <m>0_R</m> is the additive identity in <m>R</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          For inverses:
          <me>(a+I) + ((-a)+I) = (a+(-a)) + I = 0_R + I</me>
          and so the additive inverse of <m>a+I</m> is <m>-a+I</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          We now turn to the multiplicative axioms plus commutativity. For associativity:
          <md>
            <mrow> (a+I)((b+I)(c+I))\amp= (a+I)(bc+I) </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp= a(bc) + I </mrow>
            <mrow> ((a+I)(b+I))(c+I) \amp= (ab+I)(c+I) </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp= (ab)c+I </mrow>
          </md>
          But multiplication in <m>R</m> is associative so that <m>a(bc) = (ab)c</m>. Hence,
          <me>a(bc)+I = (ab)c+I.</me>
        </p>
        <p>
          For commutativity:
          <me>(a+I)(b+I) = (ab)+I = (ba)+I = (b+I)(a+I).</me>
        </p>
        <p>
          For identity:
          <me>(1_R+I)(a+I) = (1_R\cdot a)+I = a+I</me>
          as <m>1_R</m> is the multiplicative identity in <m>R</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Since <m>R/I</m> has commutative multiplication we only need to check the left-distributive axiom. 
          <md>
            <mrow>(a+I)( (b+I) + (c+I)) \amp= (a+I)( (b+c) + I) </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp= (a(b+c)) + I </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp= (ab+ac) + I</mrow>
            <mrow>(a+I)(b+I)+ (a+I)(c+I) \amp= (ab)+I + (ac)+I </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp= (ab+ac) + I </mrow>
          </md>
          where we have used that multiplication in <m>R</m> has the left-distributive property in line 3.
        </p>
        <p>
          We conclude that <m>R/I</m> is a commutative ring.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>
    
    <p>
    Thus, given a ring <m>R</m> and ideal <m>I</m> of <m>R</m>, we may build the quotient ring <m>R/I</m>.
    </p>
    
    <activity>
