    <subsection xml:id="ssec_NoetherIsomorphismTheorem">
    	<title>Noether Isomorphism Theorem</title>
    	
    	<p>
    		As quotient rings provide fertile soil for building new examples of rings, it should not surprise us to find that homomorphisms interact with quotient rings in interesting and useful ways.
    		Chief among them are the <em>isomorphism theorems</em>. In this subsection, we focus primarily on the Noether Isomorphism Theorem (also 
        called the First Isomorphism Theorem).
    	</p>
    	
    	<p>
    		We have seen that any homomorphism <m>\varphi\colon R\to S</m> gives rise to an ideal of <m>R</m>, namely <m>\ker\varphi</m>. 
    		Our next theorem demonstrates that, given a commutative ring <m>R</m>, every ideal is the kernel of 
        some homomorphism defined on <m>R</m>. In particular, our definition of ideal accurately captured what it meant to be a kernel.
    	</p>

    	<theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be commutative and <m>I</m> an ideal of <m>R</m>.
          Define <m>\varphi\colon R\to R/I</m> by <m>\varphi(r) = r+I</m>.
          Then <m>\varphi</m> is an epimorphism with <m>\ker\varphi = I</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          We first verify that <m>\varphi</m> is a homomorphism. Note that <m>\varphi(1_R) = 1_R+I</m> which 
          is the multiplicative identity in <m>R/I</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          For compatibility with addition:
          <me>\varphi(a+b) = a+b+I = (a+I) + (b+I) = \varphi(a) + \varphi(b).</me>
        </p>
        <p>
          For compatibility with multiplication:
          <me>\varphi(ab) = ab+I = (a+I)(b+I) = \varphi(a)\varphi(b).</me>
          Thus <m>\varphi</m> is a homomorphism.
        </p>
        <p>
          That <m>\varphi</m> is surjective is clear: for any <m>a+I\in R/I</m> we have <m>\varphi(a)  = a+I</m>. Lastly, suppose 
          <m>\varphi(x) = 0_R + I</m>. Then <m>x+I = 0_R+I</m> so that <m>x\in I</m>. Thus <m>\ker\varphi\subseteq I</m>. Also for any 
          <m>x\in I</m> we have <m>\varphi(x) = x+ I = I</m> so that <m>x\in \ker\varphi</m> which shows <m>\ker\varphi = I</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>
    
    <p>
      This is just a generalization of <xref ref="thm_reductionModuloMIsHomomorphism"/>.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      We work toward a proof of the Noether Isomorphism Theorem for Rings. The proof will proceed by a sequence of lemmas.
    </p>
    <p>
      Throughout, let <m>R</m> and <m>S</m> be commutative rings,
      and let <m>\varphi\colon R\to S</m> be a homomorphism.
      Recall that 
      <me>
        \mathrm{im} \varphi = \{s\in S\mid \varphi(r) = s\text{ for some } r\in R\}
      </me> 
      is a subring of <m>S</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Define <m>f\colon R/\ker \varphi \to \mathrm{im} \varphi</m> by <m>f(r+\ker \varphi) = \varphi(r)</m>.
    </p>
    <lemma>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Using the notation from above, <m>f</m> is a well-defined function.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </lemma>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Suppose that <m>r_1 + \ker\varphi = r_2 + \ker\varphi</m>.
        Then <m>r_2-r_1 \in \ker\varphi</m>,
        so <m>\varphi(r_2-r_1) = 0_S</m>, and thus <m>\varphi(r_1) = \varphi(r_2)</m>.
        Therefore, <m>f(r_1+\ker\varphi) = f(r_2+\ker\varphi)</m>,
        and <m>f</m> is well-defined.
      </p>
    </proof>

    <lemma>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Using the notation above, <m>f</m> is a homomorphism.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </lemma>

    <proof>
      <p>
        We have <m>f(1_R+\ker\varphi) = \varphi(1_R) = 1_S</m> as <m>\varphi</m> is a homomorphism.
      </p>
      <p>
        We show that <m>f</m> preserves addition.
        That it preserves multiplication will follow similarly. We compute:
        <md>
          <mrow> f((x+\ker\varphi) + (y+\ker\varphi)) \amp= f((x+y)+\ker\varphi) </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp= \varphi(x+y) </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp= \varphi(x)+\varphi(y) </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp= f(x+\ker\varphi) + f(y+\ker\varphi)</mrow>
        </md>
        where we have used that <m>\varphi</m> is a homomorphism in line 2.
      </p>
    </proof>

    <lemma>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Using the notation above, <m>f</m> is one-to-one.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </lemma>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Suppose that <m>f(r_1 + \ker\varphi) = f(r_2 + \ker\varphi)</m>.
        That is, <m>\varphi(r_1) = \varphi(r_2)</m>.
        Then <m>\varphi(r_1 - r_2) = 0_S</m>,
        so <m>r_1 -r_2 \in \ker\varphi</m>,
        and therefore <m>r_1 + \ker\varphi = r_2 + \ker \varphi</m>.
        Thus, <m>f</m> is one-to-one.
      </p>
    </proof>
    <lemma>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Using the notation above, <m>f</m> is onto.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </lemma>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Since <m>\varphi</m> is onto <m>\mathrm{im} \varphi</m> by definition,
        given any <m>s\in \mathrm{im} \varphi</m> there is some <m>r\in R</m> such that <m>\varphi(r) = s</m>.
        Then <m>f(r+\ker\varphi) = \varphi(r)</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
    <p>
      We thus obtain the following, due to Emmy Noether:
    </p>
    <theorem>
    	<idx>First Isomorphism Theorem</idx>
      <idx><h>Noether Isomorphism Theorem</h></idx>
      <title>Noether's Isomorphism Theorem</title>
      <creator>E. Noether</creator>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\varphi \colon R\to S</m> be a homomorphism of commutative rings.
          Then <m>R/\ker \varphi \cong \mathrm{im} \varphi</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          In particular,
          if <m>\varphi \colon R\to S</m> is an epimorphism (it is onto), <m>R/\ker \varphi \cong S</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    
    <p>
    	The Noether Isomorphism Theorem gives a useful way of establishing an isomorphism between a 
      quotient ring <m>R/I</m> and another ring <m>S</m>: find an onto homomorphism <m>R\to S</m> with kernel <m>I</m>.
    </p>

  </subsection>
    <subsection xml:id="subsec-">
      <title>Applying the Noether Isomorphism Theorem</title>
      
      <p>
        In the next three examples, we make heavy use of the evaluation homomorphism. We prove three separate isomorphisms using it.
      </p>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          There is an isomorphism of rings <m>\Z[x]/(x)\cong \Z</m>. Indeed, let us consider the evaluation homomorphism
          <me>\mathrm{ev}_0\colon\Z[x]\to \Z</me>
          defined by <m>\mathrm{ev}_0(f(x)) = f(0)</m>. We have seen it is a homomorphism in Exercise??? 
        </p>
        <p>
          Evaluation is an epimorphism: Pick any <m>a\in\Z</m> and consider the polynomial <m>f(x) = a</m>. Then <m>\mathrm{ev}_0(f(x)) = f(0) = a</m>.
          Since evaluation is a surjective homomorphism it is an epimorphism.
        </p>
        <p>
          We claim the kernel of evaluation at zero is <m>(x)</m>. Suppose <m>f(x) = a_0+a_1x+\cdots + a_nx^n\in \ker\mathrm{ev}_0</m>. Then 
          <me>0 = \mathrm{ev}_0(f(x)) = a_0</me>
          and so <m>a_0 = 0</m>. We conclude 
          <me>f(x) = a_1x+\cdots + a_nx^n = x(a_1+\cdots +a_nx^{n-1})</me>.
          and so <m>f(x)\in (x)</m>. Thus <m>\ker\mathrm{ev}_0(f(x)) = (x)</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          By the Noether Isomorphism Theorem we have <m>\Z[x]/(x)\cong \Z</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      The previous example illustrates the power of the evaluation mapping. Here's another (similar) example.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          There is an isomorphism of rings <m>\Q[x]/(x-5)\cong \Q</m>. Indeed, let us consider the evaluation at <m>5</m> mapping:
          <me>\mathrm{ev}_5\colon\Q[x]\to\Q</me>
          defined by <m>\mathrm{ev}_5(f(x)) = f(5)</m>. It is a homomorphism and, in a manner similar to the previous example but using polynomial
          division, we can see that <m>\ker\mathrm{ev}_5 = (x-5)</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
          The evaluation at <m>5</m> mapping is an epimorphism as for any <m>r\in\Q</m> we have <m>\mathrm{ev}_5(r) = r</m>. By the Noether Isomorphism 
          Theorem <m>\Q[x]/(x-5)\cong \Q</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Of course nothing is special about <m>5</m> here. You will prove a general theorem in Exercise????
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex_algebraicDefinitionC">
      <title>Algebraic Definition of Complex Numbers</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          At this point, we've seen two different incarnations of the complex numbers. Refernce definition and Example ?????
          We will show yet another way of constructing them.
        </p>
        <p>
          Let <m>\mathrm{ev}_i\colon\R[x]\to\C</m> be the evaluation at <m>i</m> mapping. Evaluation is a homomorphism. Let's also note that 
          <m>\mathrm{ev}_i(a+bx) = a+bi</m>. Thus <m>\mathrm{ev}_i</m> is an epimorphism.
        </p>
        <p>
          Since <m>\mathrm{ev}_i(x^2+1) = i^2+1 = -1+1 = 0</m> we know that <m>x^2+1\in\ker\mathrm{ev}_i</m>. When we get to factorizations in the next chapter 
          we will use the division algorithm to revisit this example and prove that <m>\ker\mathrm{ev}_i = (x^2+1)</m>. At the moment we do not yet have the Euclidean 
          Algorithm at our disposal. Nevertheless, it is true so by the Noether Isomorphism Theorem <m>\R[x]/(x^2+1)\cong\C</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
          One could redefine the complex numbers as <m>\R[x]/(x^2+1)</m> and this is a purely algebraic definition of <m>\C</m> (up to using <m>\R</m>).
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    
